  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">GCR Legal and social support in Lesvos</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">GCR will support persons of concern to access and exercise their legal and social rights, to receive the protective services they need, with a focus on the identification and support of those most vulnerable amongst them. Apart from the provision of legal and social assistance to asylum - seekers, GCR#s staff has already identified that some of the cases must be provided with non - asylum related social and legal aid, making sure that those persons will also receive the adequate services . The legal teamwill provide individual legal casework and counsel to beneficiaries in relation to the process of making an application for relocation, family reunification, and asylum procedures according to Greek and European legal frameworks &lt;(&gt;&amp;&lt;)&gt; procedures. The legal casework will be supported by social workers who will work alongside the legal team in conducting individual vulnerability assessments and preparing socialhistory reports, offering short - term psychosocial support, crisis intervention and referrals in reference to managing individual cases. This will include case - management of a small number of complex cases referred by Oxfam and its partners.</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="24">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Founded in 1989, the Greek Council for Refugees provides legal assistance and social support to asylum seekers and refugees; facilitates their social integration and promotes their legal and social rights. GCR#s work includes: social counseling, support for accommodation, education, work and other integration issues; free legal counseling and representation before the asylum authorities, the Hellenic Police, national courts and other judicial and administrative authorities as per need; border monitoring;educational and cultural activities for asylum seekers and refugees, including children; advocacy and promotion of refugee rights (participation in national and international networks, campaigns and several other fora;  implementation of seminars for thepolice, local administrations, lawyers, prosecutors and judges; raising awareness in Greek schools); reporting to international and national relevant institutions and bodies on the asylum situation in Greece. GCR is governed by an elected Board of Directors and employs more than 100 members of staff, including social workers, lawyers, interpreters, project managers, communication officers and other supporting personne</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Greek Council for Refugees</narrative>
  </participating-org>
